 The early Roman historian Tacitus recorded in his AD 98 writing “De Origine et situ Germanorum”, which told of the origins of the Germans, that “I should regard (The Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive.......Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?(SIC)” (Tacitus, 98) 

And who would leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, not yet at least. They would send out their conquests into the lands of Germania for goods, and lead the occasional land campaign but in the end they mostly returned back home to their sprawling empire. So as the Germanic tribes began appearing in the middle of the first century, they lived on the borders of the Roman Empire and traded their goods taken from the land, and their skills by serving within the ranks of the Roman army, (Ozment, 2005 pg. 17.)

The play Twelfth Night seems to say that although disguise is in fact useful in perpetrating long bouts of deception, in the end a person must reject that newly formed guise, or else risk losing themselves forever in the process. A big problem with ending a deception, however, is that one may find themselves alienated in the process. Therefore, in the end, one must decide between one’s own self preservation, or the preservation of relationships with those around them. For although some will respond neutrally to discovering that they’ve been tricked, still others will not take the deception so lightly, and will be likely be offended by the whole charade.
The topic of deception in gender role reversal is especially problematic, because it brings up many side issues, perhaps the most important one being, why? Why does the subject feel the need to shirk their own identity and take up a disguise in the form of the opposite gender? In Viola’s case, it is obviously a form of self protection.: “I’ll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count…” (5.1.247-249)
Having newly arrived in a foreign land, Viola feels it necessary to pretend to be a man to protect herself from would be attackers. Viola’s plan works, but it also alienates her from the women around her, cutting her off from an important support system. To make matters worse, she is apparently so convincing at appearing to be a man that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian, and in effect falls in love with her. “Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay.” (5.1.138) On top of that, she also has to deal with suppressed romantic desires between her and Orsino: “Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me.” (5.1. 260-261)
Although this may be a somewhat progressive attitude, to the modern reader, Twelfth Night may be seen as an illustration of how deception may help facilitate the unveiling of suppressed emotions, especially in the cases of Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages seem to hint that the aforesaid characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that the appearance of Viola/Cesario forces them to deal with. For instance, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because Cesario appears to be a man, or does Olivia really secretly harbor feelings for women? One would argue that this is probably not the case, because Shakespeare’s character Olivia seems more likely to be parodying those people of his time period who judge others only upon their looks. 
This is evidenced by the ease with which Olivia switches her romantic ardors from Cesario to Sebastian, and begins to regard Cesario/Viola as family rather than a love interest: “A sister, you are she.” (5.1.315)

German colonial rule has been noted by various observers for its brutality, notably with respect to the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. Of course nothing so broad as an entire colonial empire can be accounted for by such a simple description. The German colonial empire was as varied in policies and ruling style as it was in geography. Educational provision across the colonies was similarly diverse. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they found a large population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Kamerun and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors. 
The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) presented a stark contrast.  Unlike in East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a prominent role in the education of the natives, in South West Africa the task of native education was left almost entirely to missionary societies that received limited government support. The government did however invest significant resources towards the education of Europeans in the colony, establishing s system of state schools as well as more heavily supporting and regulating missionary schools. These educational policies had longstanding effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies boasted significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa “the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate.” Various social, political, and economic factors led to the divergent experience of South West Africa. This paper seeks to expand the discussion by identifying these factors and paying particular attention to new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities to native Africans.
There is a wealth of literature dealing with education in the German colonial empire specifically. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The aim of early works was primarily to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies illustrated significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work to explicitly address the topic of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors that account for the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa explains many of the distinguishing aspects of the colony’s educational system.
Compared to Germany’s other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected the relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913 nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, while only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

The United States of America and Mexico are an example of two nations which at one time were beset by an enduring rivalry which spanned 57 years, from 1836 to 1893. (Diehl and Goerts 2000 p. 145).  The high-water mark of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, where the United States attacked and defeated Mexico and secured for itself Texas and the American Southwest as new territory.  Many other clashes happened between the two nations, finally abating just before the First World War.   The rivalry began as Americans and Mexicans clashed on key issues such as religion, culture and tradition and had a major clash of material interests (Schmitt 1974 p. 30-31).   
	This is not unlike many other nations who have an enduring rivalry with a neighbor.  Nations which share a border tend to have clashes of interests which lend to the creation of rival positions between the nations.  The United States and Mexico are not unlike many other enduring rivalries between nations which share a common border.  David M. Pletcher (1977) states that “Only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems” (p. 41).  Indeed, both of these nations are geographically close to the United States and have been rivals to the United States, while other nations in Latin America enjoy and have enjoyed good relations with the United States.   
	Religious issues created a rift between the two nations, a problem which has beset many nations through history.  Sally Frahm (2001) states that ”if in the twentieth century Americans were opposed to fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth they were opposed to Catholicism and monarchy”  (p.86).  Not unlike the Cold War’s rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union was part ideological struggle and part a competition over interests each nation deemed vital. In this case, however, the ideological struggles weren’t based on the political structure but on instead the religious preferences of the United States and Mexico.  This distrust grew from the distrust between the English and Spanish.  Inheriting these feelings of distrust from their former colonial rulers was a major obstacle in the establishment of amiable foreign relations between the United States and Mexico.
	Diehl and Goerts (2000) list 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States in the 57-year rivalry period.   The majority of disputes between the rivalry period described by Diehl and Goerts are territorial issues relating to border raids from Mexican territory into Mexico and other frontier problems.  Border raids by bandits and outlaws from on American border towns were a major problem which remained until both the United States and Mexico exerted military force on their borders (Schmitt 1974 p. 97).  
Schmitt (1974) explains the rivalry between the two nation began to abate as “Mexico became clearly dependent on the United States in a substantial way” (p. 109) and finally ended as American ambitions “changed from territorial expansion to economic intervention into Mexico” (p.110) in the later part of the 19th Century.

Fifteen‭ ‬years ago I became suddenly and unexpectedly disabled by an illness I never knew existed. 

 I was a nurse at the time. I had chosen my profession out of a deeply entrenched need for the safety and security I didn't have as a child. ‭"‬You'll always be able to find work‭; ‬people will always get sick.‭" ‬was the mantra I heard over and over as I reached adolescence and beyond. So--‭ ‬even though my dream was to be a scientist or a journalist-preferably a little of both,‭ ‬I chose nursing. 

Nevertheless,‭ ‬there I was:‭ ‬46‭ ‬years old and single,‭ ‬no money in the bank to speak of and unable to work. To this day I am disabled,‭ ‬and after‭ ‬15‭ ‬years of living on Social Security Disability,‭ ‬I have literally nothing left that I can call‭ "‬mine.‭" ‬I get by,‭ ‬but every day is a struggle and an assault on my security,‭ ‬safety and self-esteem. Nothing in my life is certain anymore,‭ ‬yet,‭ ‬there is one thing that I know to be true. I could not have gotten by for all these years were it not for the help of my family and a few good friends,‭ ‬no matter how strong I was. And believe me,‭ ‬when real disaster strikes,‭ ‬you do not feel very strong at all. 

My point is that there will always be emergencies in life-big and small.  There are no guarantees and no matter how well one prepares,‭ ‬some things are just too big to overcome on your own. 

I agree wholeheartedly that we in the U.S. need to stop putting all of our eggs in big government's‭ "‬basket‭"; ‬Lord knows it is moldy‭ ‬and falling apart,‭ ‬anyway. Yet I would much rather see Americans learning to trust one another again‭–‬learning to help each other and to ask for help,‭ ‬rather‭ ‬than have each of us individually clambering out to the backyard to build fallout shelters. 

The Conservatives in the US talk about the‭ "‬rugged individualism‭" ‬that built this country‭; ‬but in truth,‭ ‬what kept our forefathers going in hard times wasn't rugged individualism,‭ ‬it was compassion,‭ ‬mutual respect and the sharing of resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains didn't make it to the coast by going it alone. 


So,‭ ‬by all means,‭ ‬be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit‭; ‬first‭ ‬aid supplies,‭ ‬water purifying tablets and plastic sheeting and duct tape for the windows in the event of a biological attack. I have several flashlights and all sorts of batteries,‭ ‬lots and lots of candles and waterproof matches and canned goods,‭ ‬too. If‭ ‬you have the land and the resources for a small farm and the ability to can or preserve your own food-do it. It's a great idea,‭ ‬as is a wood stove,‭ ‬as long as you do not live in an apartment. 

But while you are at it,‭ ‬get to know your neighbors.

Sometime in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince who would one day be called Buddha was born. Over the course of his life, he renounced the world and became enlightened, and his teachings led to the formation of Buddhism—the most orthodox sect of which is known as Theravada Buddhism. The religion is around twenty five hundred years old; it looks different today than it did when Buddha was alive. This can be seen all over, for instance in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is observed. Monks and laymen alike participate in this ceremony, and it holds some religious significance, despite Buddha never teaching about any festivity of the sort. These differences run all the way from the superficial traditions to the soteriological core of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community, both from the monastic perspective and from the lay perspective, has had to change its doctrinal principles over time. This can be attributed to forces both external and internal, both hostile and benign.
	There are a number of qualifying terms this discussion will make frequent use of. There is the concept of internal versus external. Here, an internal force is defined as a force borne of members of the Buddhasasana, regardless of monastic status. An external force is any force from non-Buddhists. A hostile force is any force that damages or intends to damage the Buddhist community—a force borne of a negative perception of Buddhism. A benign force is a force that does not wish to harm or help the Buddhist community—though it may end up doing one or the other as a byproduct. These terms will come up repeatedly throughout this discussion.
	First, it is important to investigate the basics of the religion—the doctrines that lie at the core of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem of the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma is essentially comprised of the Tripitaka—the three baskets—of Buddhist text. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka contains the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka contains the metaphysical components of Buddhism. The metaphysical notions consist of things like Anatta—no soul, Dukkha—inherent suffering in life, and Anicca—impermanence of everything. Only by recognizing these concepts can one end Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, which happens continuously. Along with Sansara will end lobha—desire, dosa—hatred, and moha—delusion, when one becomes enlightened. In the Vinaya Pitaka, rules for life are set forth. For laymen, there are five precepts (I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not misbehave sexually, and I shall not take intoxicating substances). For monks, there are many more disciplinary rules to be followed. The most fundamental doctrinal notion in Buddhism is the notion of the four noble truths. First, Dukkha; the truth that life is suffering. Second, that attachment causes suffering. Third, that suffering can be overcome.
transformed_texts: I want to have a job in social work. I will work with the Division of Family and Children Services. I will help children who have been hurt or neglected. I will also help troubled families. I have some values that are good for this work: service, respect, and ethics. I also want to get better at my job. These values are important to me personally. I always wanted to help other people. I was not sure what job to do. Some people in high school and college did not deal with their problems well. Some used bad coping ways. I saw this. So, I studied psychology in college. I was still unsure of a job. After college, I took a break. One day, I visited a friend. She had a sixteen-year-old boy. He was scared. His parents were hurtful. I drove to his house. The police were there. They asked me to talk to his parents. They were nervous and made up stories about their son. After that, I thought about working in social work. I want to help children with small family problems. I believe in social justice. In society, we say each person is important. But society always wants people to be the same. I do not like this. At school, I protested against injustice. I will continue to protest against it. I believe in being unique and fighting for equality.

This paper discusses biological and sociocultural models of insomnia. The biological model looks at genes and medical issues. The sociocultural model focuses on relationships and effects on race, ethnicity, and economic status.

The paper reviews insomnia using these models. It explains each study and its results. Then, it discusses the strengths and weaknesses of these studies.

A sleep disorder can be a primary, related, or caused by other issues. Primary sleep disorders are Dyssomnias and Parasomnias. They include Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, and Narcolepsy. Parasomnias involve behavior and physical issues like Nightmare Disorder and Sleepwalking Disorder. Related sleep disorders are caused by mental disorders or medical problems.

The biological model of sleep disorders studies genes and physiological factors. Orexin neurons in the hypothalamus control sleep and wakefulness. Research with mice found GABAB receptors control sleep and wake states. If these receptors do not work well, people may not sleep well. This study shows a genetic basis for sleep disorders. If the receptors do not work properly, it can affect daily life.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD) is a problem with how the brain uses sounds. People with CAPD can hear normally, but their brain has trouble understanding and interpreting what they hear.

CAPD was first called "auditory imperception" in the 1950s. The Italian team of Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari started tests for children with this problem in 1954. In 1961, Kimura introduced a test called dichotic testing. This test helps understand how the brain processes sounds. A national conference in 1977 pushed more research on CAPD.

People with CAPD may have problems like:
- Not hearing sounds in space
- Not understanding different sounds
- Not recognizing sound patterns
- Not understanding changes in speech
- Not being able to hear one sound over another
- Not understanding sound clues
- Not remembering the order of sounds

To diagnose CAPD, doctors screen for these problems. They use tests and observe how the person listens. There is no one test that works for everyone. Many tests present multiple sounds at once and ask the person to pick out certain ones. Some advanced tests record sounds in the ear and measure responses.

The play Twelfth Night says that while hiding can help fake for a long time, a person must stop the trick or lose themselves forever. One big problem is that stopping the trick may be lonely. Some people will not be happy when they know they were tricked. The play has a problem about hiding in a different gender. For example, Viola pretends to be a man to protect herself in a new place. Her trick works, but she cannot be friends with women. Viola also makes Olivia think she is Sebastian and fall in love with her. Viola also has to hide her love for Orsino. The play shows how hiding can show hidden feelings. It is not clear why Viola pretends to be a man. Maybe Olivia likes Cesario because he looks like a man, or maybe she really likes women. The play shows that Olivia might not care about looks. She quickly changes her love from Cesario to Sebastian, and thinks Cesario is her sister.

German colonial power was bad. This is true, especially with the Ovaherero and Nama people in German South West Africa. German rule was not the same everywhere. It changed by place. For example, in German East Africa (Tanganyika), the Germans did good things for education. But in South West Africa (now Namibia), the Germans did not do as much. The German government did not help much with native education. Instead, they left it to missionary groups with little support. The German government did help European education, though. This was different from other colonies. After German rule, South West Africa had many uneducated people. Many things made this happen. This paper looks at these things, with special attention to new information about settlers and leaders' views of the natives.

There is much writing about education in the German colonies, mostly in German. Early books talked about how education worked there. Later books talked more about how different colonies were. Cohen's study is the best for this topic. Cohen compared South West Africa and East Africa. He says the big settler population in South West Africa explains how education was different there.

South West Africa was not as hot as other colonies. This was good for Europeans. There were more white people living there. By 1913, there were almost 15,000 whites in South West Africa, while East Africa had only 5,336.

The music called popular music has grown for many years. It has many kinds, like rock, rap, country, and jazz. Many of these kinds have smaller kinds inside them. One of these kinds is heavy metal rock. This kind is very different and has many sub-kinds. It started about 40 years ago. It has many dark feelings and it is very loud. People use drugs to make the music. Many people like to play in this kind of music. It is hard to say what heavy metal is today. It has many themes from other kinds of music. To understand the music today, we must first understand what heavy metal is and why it is a movement, not just a kind of music.

Metal is a kind of music that has dark feelings. It is loud and violent. It is different from other kinds of music because it is not primitive. People who play it are good musicians. Many people use drugs to make the music. In the past, drugs made people make music that was very strange and different. This music was a new kind of music.

Heavy metal music has dark, strong feelings. It is not like other music that is not dark. It has dark feelings like the Romantic Era music had. Some of the lyrics of this music talk about dark feelings, like the lyrics from the song Helter Skelter. This song is one of the first heavy metal songs. It talks about dark feelings and it is loud. This song was a reply to a song by the Rolling Stones. The Beatles made this song to show they could make loud, dark music. This song is called Helter Skelter and it is on their album called The White Album.

Henri Rousseau dreamed of being a famous painter. He painted many pictures. One of his most famous paintings is "The Dream". This painting shows a woman in a dream. It also shows Rousseau's dreams and goals. He wanted other artists and art lovers to praise and accept him. This was hard for him. He had to decide if he should paint like other artists or paint his own way. He started painting late in life. He worked for many years before he got famous. He was not as educated as other artists. He started painting because he was sad after his wife and children died. He wanted to paint to make himself feel better. He wanted to be accepted by the art world. He was not like other artists. He was a simple painter. He wanted to paint simply and be accepted.

Many thinkers think art and ethics are related. They connect truth and beauty. We learn ethics and aesthetics from life and experience. We try to describe why something is good or beautiful, not just judge it. We cannot fully explain art or morals. A story's something extra is important. This is true for ethics too. We feel ethics and art strongly. They cannot be fully explained. They connect at a deep level. Literature is unique because it shows values like life does.

Today's Germany is strong. It is a united country. Its culture is unique. This culture can be seen from Munich to Kiel. It is also felt in Cologne and Dresden. This culture comes from many sources and tribes.

The name of Germany has different meanings. Some say it comes from a tribe called the Tungrians. Others say it means a type of spear. Another idea is that it means to shout in old Irish.

A Roman historian named Tacitus wrote about the Germans in 98 AD. He said they were original. He said they came from ships. He asked why anyone would leave a warm place like Rome to go to cold Germany.

The Romans did not conquer Germany. They traded with the Germans and sometimes fought them. The Romans wanted goods and skills from the Germans. So, the Germans lived at the edge of the Roman Empire.

I looked down. My mind was empty. I saw a picture. I did not feel anything. I was not thinking about it. I was just looking. I saw it but did not think about it.
I bought a book called The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain. I wanted to learn to draw. This book teaches how to understand lines and shapes.
The book says to put a square around any picture you want to study. I tried this with a bowl of fruit. I could not do it at first. I was too overwhelmed. I just stared.
I thought about famous artists. Picasso, Monet, and Italian Renaissance masters. I wanted to be like them. I saw a start of my own story. I named it "Work in Brown."
I touched my pencil. My hand moved. My mind wanted to make something. Water swirled. I tried to move the toilet paper. It was stuck. I tried again. It did not move.
I was upset. I stared at the paper. I thought about cleaning it. I started. I put my hand in the toilet. I felt like a mother with a turkey for Thanksgiving.

Teenagers die in car accidents.  Many causes work together to create this deadly problem for young American drivers.  The National Institutes of Health say the teen brain is not ready for driving.  Lack of experience also causes more crashes.  This includes fatal accidents, rollovers, speeding, and driving off the road.
Teens also have more crashes when they drive with friends.  A study shows this.  California and other states try to make teens safer by limiting driving hours and stopping teens from having other teens as passengers.  But these are not enough.  Teens are simply not ready to drive well.  Dr. Marvin Zuckerman says 18 is too young for a regular driver’s license.
Young teens want to take risks.  It makes sense to delay driving until this desire fades.  If teens keep getting driver’s licenses, more accidents will happen.  By 2010, many more teens will be eligible and ready to drive.
Simple legislation could help.  Schools could teach driving, but teens under 18 could not drive.  A provisional permit would still be needed for a full license.  Teens would need more behind-the-wheel training.  Many states already require this.  This could be a national law to protect teens.
This idea is not new.

I looked at the Library of Congress's early Edison films. I found fifteen trick films from 1895 to 1901. These films use creative editing to show illusions. I studied the films to describe trick film poetics and find special characteristics in some later films.

Most trick films from the turn of the century are set-bound. They are composed in a frontal proscenium. The camera does not move. It uses long and medium shots. They follow the rule that one conceptual shot equals one film. This makes most trick films short, about one minute or less.

Trick films also share a common filming style. They are shot in a set within the frame of a proscenium. The camera does not move to follow figures or objects. This is like the theatre and vaudeville tradition. Actors in trick films only move side-to-side. They do not walk towards or away from the camera. For example, in Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), actors move from right to left and back.

The films use long and medium shots. Close-up shots are not used. This is because the audience sees the whole performance at once, like in the theatre. Actors do not move towards the camera, so close-ups do not happen.

Most trick films have one conceptual shot for each film. This limits the length and story of the films. Most trick films are short vaudeville tricks. However, one conceptual shot may have many physical shots. Look at The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895). The film is one conceptual shot, but has many physical shots.

John Taylor from Caroline was a strong supporter of Republican ideas. He liked farming and had a short time in politics too. These activities helped him become a person who spoke strongly about personal freedom and government. He thought farming was the best job, and it helped him have many ideas about the government.

Taylor thought the United States could create a good system because there were no old traditions to stop it. He believed in natural rights. These rights are important for all people and should not be controlled by the government. He said that in a good society, people with power and bad ideas should not do as they wish.

To make a good society, Taylor said the government must understand good and bad in people. He thought that good ideas protect private property, help farming, and stop big businesses. He said a good government should always protect these ideas, even if people in charge are selfish.

Taylor wanted a small government with only the powers listed in the Constitution. He did not want a big, expensive government that could abuse power. He also said that the Declaration of Independence is the true rule of the United States, not just the Constitution.

In Figure 17, we see a big drop in commuter log submissions in the third month. This was a bit discouraging. The reason might be winter in New England, which makes people not commute by bike or walking. Also, December is the end of the fall semester. People might forget to fill out the log with all the school tasks. The holiday season brings a month-long break for students and faculty, so many people do not need to come to campus. Classes start again in late January, but this did not explain the low number of logs in February. The project started with high energy, which might naturally decrease. We had the Carpool Challenge Week in March to get more log submissions. Another challenge is that people love driving cars. We gave out gift certificates for local stores, but bigger prizes could have helped. If prizes increased over time, engagement might have gone up instead of down.

An ETF is a type of investment that follows a market index, commodity, or group of assets. It is traded like a stock. ETFs have low costs but you pay a fee for each trade. They offer many different funds. It's important to check if the stated benefits like diversification really exist. We will look at the ETF IHF and compare it to the top 10 stocks it holds. We will see if the benefits of owning the ETF are like owning many stocks. We will also check if there are better ways to buy these stocks. We will look at the top 10 stocks that make up 63.58% of the ETF. Below is the list of these stocks and the percentage they make up.

To check how well these stocks represent the ETF, we will use the current percentage of each stock. We will calculate the Beta and Return of a portfolio of these stocks. The chart below shows these calculations.

From the chart, a portfolio of just the top 10 stocks gives a 6.11% higher return than the ETF. It also has a 0.12 lower Beta. It seems a portfolio of the top 10 stocks could give better returns with less risk. However, the portfolios' means may not be different. To check this, we will calculate the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks and compare them to the ETF IHF.

Poe's poem "Dream-Land" uses the word "Thulé" twice. In "Dream-Land," Poe uses language and ideas from another writer, Goethe. Goethe's poem "The King of Thulé" is about a king who loses his wife and becomes sad. Poe's poem shows similarities to Goethe's. Poe's poem uses the idea of Thulé to describe a dark, lonely place where the speaker feels haunted. This shows Poe's interest in and knowledge of Goethe's work. Poe also uses the word Thulé in another poem, "The Pit and the Pendulum." Goethe's "Faust," a famous poem, was published around the time Poe wrote "Dream-Land." This shows that Poe was influenced by Goethe's work. Goethe was a famous author. Poe admired Tennyson, and he likely knew about Goethe's work because of Tennyson's respect for Goethe.

A customer who slipped and fell in a grocery store after an applesauce spill could get punitive damages if the store manager knew about the spill twice but did not clean it. The store manager was eating dinner and did not have time to clean the spill. The customer could argue that the manager's actions were wrong and could cause harm. The manager knew that others slipped before, but still did not clean the spill. The judge might not dismiss the claim quickly.

On October 13, 2009, an employee told the manager about the spill. The manager was having dinner and did not clean it. Another employee also told the manager, but he did not clean it either. At 5:30 pm, the customer slipped and fell on the spill and got hurt. The store had many slip-and-fall accidents before. The customer is now suing for damages, and the store is thinking about dismissing the claim.

In California, the law says a customer can get punitive damages if the store acted with "oppression, fraud or malice." The law says malice is when the manager knew that his actions would cause harm, or did not care about the harm. The judge might think the manager's actions were malicious because he was aware of the danger and did not act.

Four years ago, I studied Islam at CBC. The class discussed if Islam was a hostile religion. This question is still important today. After 9/11, the media changed from being against Islam to being very tolerant. In 2001, a president with a Muslim name couldn't have been possible.

The Prophet's biography is interesting because it doesn't match what I know about Muhammad. I thought Muhammad forced people to become Muslims. But the biography says he was a peaceful man who helped others. People eventually believed in his teachings.

The biography also has many stories about Muhammad's miracles. One story tells how he multiplied food for forty men. This makes Muhammad seem humble and truthful. However, it makes Jesus' life seem less important.

The biography also tries to prove people converted to Islam on their own. But the stories are often from third parties. This makes the stories seem less true.

The thing I dislike most is that the biography tries to make Muhammad seem like a good man. But history says Muhammad was not humble. Muslims today might not know the true history of Muhammad's rise to power.

Jesus's teachings and beliefs have a powerful impact on Christian thought. Over time, Christianity moved away from its origin. Today, people become aware and think in new ways. Traditional people resist new ideas, but they are not powerful enough to stop change. In the future, Christians will want to understand Jesus's true beliefs. This will take time, and the result will be a return to Jesus's original beliefs. In the United States and Europe, people will follow Jesus's teachings. The church will lead this change. The diversity of beliefs will decrease, and there will be more agreement. This has happened before in history. For example, Christianity became strong in Rome, and African-Americans went from slavery to leadership. The future will see a great change in Christianity, undoing past history and diversity. A key part of this change will be understanding Jesus's words as metaphors. What happened after Jesus's life? Looking back in history, we see only Judaism, the start of Christianity. Monotheism, revealed religion, and Hebrew scriptures were important. The Jewish population had many groups.

I think The Jungle shows people are naturally greedy and selfish. They only care about themselves and their own good life. They do not care about others, especially those lower than them. The Jungle shows this in many ways. The factory owners and managers only want big companies and factories. They do not care about people or animals hurt by their factories. They do not care about pollution. They do not care about their workers. They force workers to work long hours and may fire many people at once with no compensation or help. There were no good laws or organizations to protect workers.

The workers had no way to escape the system. They were treated like slaves. Many people lived and worked themselves to death. Unions did not help workers. They made money from them. Workers had no way to escape. This is why they were slaves.

Many writers use different ways to make readers feel or think about important things. Scott Fitzgerald does this in his book The Great Gatsby. He uses two main ways:
1. He puts together words that usually do not go together to make a strong feeling.
2. He makes a symbol and then uses it to remind readers of a feeling about a thing.

Scott Fitzgerald does this with many colors. He gives meaning to colors like white/gray and red/pink and uses them to show different feelings. In The Great Gatsby, Scott Fitzgerald shows that white/gray is like being the same or unimportant. He does this at the start of the book by saying many people wear white, like Daisy, Nick, Tom, and Catherine. He also says common things like cars, land, children, and people are white or gray. After this, he uses white/gray to show things are not important or the same.

Scott Fitzgerald shows Daisy as not important by saying she wears white and has a gray fur collar. He does this to make her seem like something Gatsby wants but not a real person. He also does this to make other things seem less important, like the gray cars and gray land he talks about earlier in the book.

San Diego County is good for farming, with many crops. The most common are tomatoes, citrus, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. There is a big market for organic food. Many farms offer tours and activities. Organic farming can help nature and wildlife. However, it is more expensive and needs more work. The land near Potrero, San Diego, is 160 acres. It has chaparral, nonnative grassland, and oak woodland. It is next to the Cleveland National Forest. Many animals live there. Some are in danger. This land was home to Native Americans and later cattle ranchers. A small farmer might get help with costs and keep the land good for animals.

Culture is important in talks. Culture is not one thing. It is not the same everywhere. It is not easy to understand one culture from another. People make generalizations about cultures. For example, all Russians may not be stubborn. All Japanese may not be easy to work with. It is better to understand how a culture feels about things. When you go to talk to people from another culture, you compare it to your own. You can learn about their history and beliefs. It is important to accept their culture. You should work with it, not try to change it. You should also respect their traditions and beliefs. This can help talks go well.

Culture is not only about countries. Companies also have their own culture. A company may have long work hours or a more relaxed schedule. A company may have rules about how people should talk or work. A company may care about helping others. Even in the same country, cultures can be different. For example, some companies in the United States may have different cultures. Some cultures are not as different as they seem. It is important to learn about a company's values. Values explain why people do things. If a company values saving face, a person will not do something to make others feel bad. If a company values hard work, a person will not settle too quickly. It is important to learn about the other person before talks. This can help talks go well.

The book says, "There is no God." This is in Psalm 14 of the Bible. It is also what Thomas Aquinas thinks. We will talk about their ideas about God. We think both of them are right about God. This helps us compare their arguments. But we must assume God is like the God in the Bible. So, we will talk about that.

Anselm's argument is about God being in our mind. He says we know God exists in our thoughts, so we don't need proof from the world. This is called faith. Aquinas thinks we can find God using logic and facts. This is good for teaching people about God. He gives five proofs: change, cause, chance, good, and harmony. He says God's existence is needed for these things.

A man born in the fifth or sixth century BCE became Buddha. His teachings made Buddhism. Theravada Buddhism is the best-known type. The religion is 2500 years old now. It was different when Buddha was alive. Today, the Theravada country of Sri Lanka has a water-cutting ceremony. This ceremony is important to monks and laypeople. They do it for religion, but Buddha never taught about it. The religion has changed because of different forces. Some are from Buddhists, others from non-Buddhists. Some forces want to harm the religion, others do not.

We will use some important words. Internal forces come from Buddhists, whether they are monks or not. External forces come from non-Buddhists. Hostile forces want to harm the Buddhist community. Benign forces do not want to harm or help. They might do one or the other accidentally.

First, let's understand the basics of the religion. Buddhists believe in three things: the Buddha, Dhamma, and Sangha. Dhamma is the Buddhist text. It has three parts: Sutta Pitaka, Vinaya Pitaka, and Abhidhamma Pitaka. The Sutta Pitaka has all the Suttas. The Vinaya Pitaka has the rules for life. The Abhidhamma Pitaka has the metaphysical parts, like Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (suffering), and Anicca (impermanence). To stop the cycle of death and rebirth (Sansara), one must know these things. Also, one must stop desire (lobha), hatred (dosa), and delusion (moha). The Vinaya Pitaka gives rules for monks and laypeople. Monks have many rules to follow. The four noble truths are the most important. First, life is suffering. Second, attachment causes suffering. Third, suffering can be ended.

The United States of America and Mexico had a long fight from 1836 to 1893. This fight was called a rivalry. The biggest fight was the Mexican-American War in 1846-1848. The United States won this war and got Texas and the American Southwest as new land. Many other fights happened between these two countries until just before World War I.

Nations that share a border often have fights over things like religion, culture, and money. The United States and Mexico were like this. David M. Pletcher said that only Mexico and Cuba had long fights with the United States. Both these countries are close to the United States and had bad relations with it.

Religion was a big reason for the fight. In the 1800s, Americans did not like Catholics and monarchies. This was like the Cold War with the Soviet Union. The fight between the United States and Mexico was not about political systems but about religion. The distrust came from the old fight between the English and Spanish.

Diehl and Goerts counted 17 fights between Mexico and the United States. Most of these fights were about territory. People from Mexico would attack American towns. Both countries used their armies to stop this.

The fight started to stop when Mexico became more dependent on the United States. Finally, it ended when American goals changed from getting new land to helping with Mexico's economy.

Fifteen years ago, I became suddenly very sick. I am a nurse. I chose this job because I wanted safety and security. But I was 46 and single. I had no money. I could not work. I am sick now and have been for 15 years. I live on Social Security. I have no money left. Every day is hard. I could not survive without family and friends. I know life has emergencies. Some are too big to handle alone. The US needs to stop relying on big government. It is not good. People should help each other. Pioneers did not succeed alone. They helped each other. I have a disaster kit. I have food and water. I know neighbors. But I also have a small farm. I can my own food. I have a wood stove. But I live in an apartment.

Why do creatures grow how they do? Are there rules that change how they grow? In 1917, D'Arcy Thompson said that even now, scientists do not use math to describe the simplest creature shapes. But today, math models are used to study how mollusk shells grow. Our study looks at how math models and experiments can explain how creatures change. We use X-ray pictures of Prunum shells to measure shell parts. These measurements are put into a program called CerioShell. We make models of how shells could change. These models are used with other studies to understand big changes in Prunum shells.

A shell is like a tube that grows over time. This tube makes turns called whorls. Each turn is around a central line called the columella. The biggest turn is at the end of the shell. The animal leaves the shell through a hole called the aperture.

Shells can be seen from different angles. The usual way is the aperture facing up. The aperture is also seen in other views, like apical and basal.

To count whorls, first look at the shell from the top. Find the first turn's start. Draw a line. Count turns from that line. Whorls are counted to a quarter turn.

A shell's growth can be shown as a path. This path can be shown with math. Once the math is made, you can change how the mollusk grows.

Indonesia’s baby and young child deaths are not improving. While the country meets some Millennium Development Goals, child and mother health is not improving enough. Here are problems and solutions.

Indonesia has 72% births with skilled workers. Traditional workers, like midwives, cannot help with complicated pregnancies. This is why many mothers die. Diarrhea treatment for young children is lower. Data on postnatal care is not complete, but rates are low.

Cesarean-section rates are low. Urban rates are higher: 7% compared to rural 2%.
This shows healthcare is not equal in Indonesia. Poor people find it harder to get care because of costs.

To improve care, Indonesia should decide between program-specific or overall health system changes. Program-specific approaches are attractive because they are targeted and quick. But, they can cause problems:
- They take funding and resources from other areas.
- They can cause duplication and uncoordinated work.

Victorian novels often focus on detail and the aristocracy. Two novels, Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, are different. They have mystery and strange things. These help the characters and show their feelings. In Oliver Twist, strange things happen in dreams. They show Oliver's mind and what hurts him. When Oliver faces danger, he can't control it. He feels pain and fear. His life is not in his hands. He feels defeated. It seems like Fagin makes him accept this.

I worked in an after school program a few years ago. I helped kids who had trouble learning. My best subject was English and reading. I helped a child named Adrian. He was in third or fourth grade. He had problems reading. Some letters he knew, others he didn't. He spoke perfect English but didn't know the alphabet well. I thought this was strange. His mother didn't speak English, only Spanish. I learned a little Spanish to talk to her. Then I understood. Adrian could read, but he didn't know the alphabet. I don't know if this helped him much, but I hope he is better now.

I tell this story to talk about the language barrier in schools, especially here in California. It's not always clear. Even if a child speaks English, they can have trouble reading. I think everyone agrees this is a problem. What can we do? For Adrian, the answer was simple: tutoring in English reading, especially the alphabet and sounds. But for many children who don't speak much English, the answer is more complex. No one thing will fix this. The best way is to combine many methods: dual language system, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes.

First, the dual language system is good. It helps all children, not just those who speak Spanish. "Children in two-way bilingual education programs do better academically." Some people think it's a waste of resources, but that's not true. If we use these programs more, all children can benefit. But how? We don't need all teachers to be bilingual. That's not realistic. But we can have special helpers who speak two languages.

From young, we learn about something big. Some go to church or look inside. Many see what parents believe. Some do not. We choose. We find light in dark. One time, my father loved birds. We sat, rain falling. He was thin, sick. I felt alone. He did not talk about death. I hugged him. I waited until he left. No one called me.

The Gothic novel is an old-new mix, as Ian Watt calls it in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. People have praised and criticized it. The original Gothic novel, Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, uses old and new ideas to start a new type of story. It mixes old theatre and new nature to show a Gothic story. Even the word 'gothic' meant different things at first. It was seen as old or simple next to new things. The mix of old theatre and new novel style helps Gothic stay popular. It also makes it seem both old and new to readers far from the time of the original writing.

One main idea in Gothic novels is Chivalry. The Gothic novel keeps some old chivalric ideas and changes them. It shows a brave, honorable knight, and the lack of these ideas in society. Walpole, who wrote The Castle of Otranto, lived in a time of political problems and was worried about the future. He might have felt that society had lost the good qualities of the Gothic past. In the story, the character Frederic has many chivalric traits. He is a prince, has suffered, and is thought to have died. His image is exaggerated to show the Gothic trope of excess.

Supply chain management is a system of actions that moves goods from customer orders to final delivery. This process includes planning, doing, and controlling all parts of the supply chain to meet customer needs quickly and efficiently. It was first described in 1982 by Keith Oliver, a consultant.

There are six main parts of a supply chain: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information. Business managers use these parts to give the best service to customers.

Production is the first step. It is the start of the supply chain. Managers must know what customers want. They look at the market to understand this. After understanding, managers decide what products to make and how many. They also decide where to make the products. Then, they plan the work and take care of the equipment.

The second part is supply. Supply managers make decisions about the main parts of the business and which outsourcing partners to work with. A company might have several parts for one product. Each part has different equipment, workers, and skills. The manager decides which part is best for each part of the product. They might also work with other companies to reduce costs.

Hitler is alive in Burma. A sign says so.

Ellen Page, star of Juno, stands alone. She holds a cardboard sign. The words are written with a Sharpie. Burma, also called Myanmar, is a country in Southeast Asia. It is ruled by a group of people called a junta. They came to power in 1962. They took control through a coup d’état. In 2007, many people protested in the streets. Monks led these protests. The protests were called "The Saffron Revolution". The government allowed the monks to gather at first. But then, the protests became violent. The military invaded and destroyed monasteries. Many people were killed. A Japanese photojournalist, Kenji Nagai, was killed on September 27, 2007. The official death toll is 13, but many more were killed. Colonel Hla Win said, "Many more people have been killed."

This is not new. Many governments want to control their people. They do not want people to protest. The Roman emperors thought they were chosen by the gods to rule. In Japan, the emperor is believed to be a god. Our president, George W. Bush, talks to Ted Haggard, leader of Stupid People Worldwide.

In 1989, many people protested in Tiananmen Square. The government killed many people. The Rwandan genocide of the 1990s was also bad. Many Tutsis were killed. Hitler's Third Reich killed many Jewish people.

Duke Ellington made jazz music for a long time. He was good at making his band sound good. He let his players play alone and together. He used their sounds to make new and good music. He did this by writing songs that showed each player’s skills. He used voices as instruments in songs like Creole Love Call. In this song, a man’s voice and the reeds (woodwinds) talk to each other. The piano plays a little bit. Then, a trumpet plays a solo. Later, the whole band plays together. The song ends with a trombone making a funny sound. This is how Ellington used voices in his music. In Hot and Bothered, he used a trumpet player and a singer to make a special sound. In It Don’t Mean a Thing, he used a trombone player to start the song on a muted trombone. This is how Ellington used his players to make good music.

She always felt she needed something. This feeling started when she was 14, a teenager. It was still there at 17. She wanted a person, not a thing. Boys did not interest her. Some tried to talk to her, but nothing appealed to her. She thought about this a lot, but had no good ideas. So, she lived her life, wondering about her desires.

Home was usually peaceful. Her parents were calm and never argued. They only argued about her independence. She was likeable and kind. Her mother was calm, but her daughter was energetic. Today was different. She heard a scream from the kitchen. Her mother was on the ground in pain. Her daughter ran to help. "Mom, what's wrong?" she asked. "Ow, I need to go to the hospital," her mother said. The daughter carried her mother to the car and drove to the hospital.

The hospital was full of disinfectant and sick smells. She didn't feel that. She was too busy helping her mother. Her mother had fallen from a step stool, trying to reach a vase. A doctor looked at her mother. The daughter waited, worried.

This study showed that following a Mediterranean diet (Med diet) can lower the risk of heart disease and stroke. The diet includes more plant foods, good fats, and fish, and less meat and saturated fats. Drinking alcohol is okay but in moderation.

Earlier research showed that the Med diet is good for overall health and weight loss. But this study looked at strokes and stroke deaths specifically.

The study followed 74,886 women, aged 38 to 63, who were nurses. They filled out food questionnaires six times over 20 years. Most nurses stayed in the study. Their health was checked regularly.

The study used special math to show the diet's effect on heart and stroke risk. It found that women who followed the diet had less risk of heart and stroke. After 20 years, 2391 heart cases and 1763 stroke cases were found. Women who followed the diet best had the least risk.

In 2007, the United States of America had a big financial problem. Many people lost their jobs, and the housing market went wrong. Big companies also had problems. This problem is still happening today. We need to know how this happened and how to stop it.

The crisis started because of bad decisions by politicians. They made banks and companies give out loans to people who could not pay back. This problem was in the financial system for a long time. In 1999, the Clinton administration changed the rules to help people get loans. They did this to be popular and make more money. A journalist said this could cause big problems. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac were pressured to give out these loans and sell them as investments. When people could not pay back, the problems got worse. The banks did not have enough money to fix the problem. This problem spread to the economy.

Many things made the economy worse. New kinds of loans, like adjustable-rate mortgages and mortgage-backed securities, were used a lot. This made the economy depend on the housing market too much. When the housing market had problems, it hurt the whole economy.

The housing market went down, and banks that bought these loans had big losses. Five big U.S. investment banks had $4.1 trillion in mortgage debts in 2007. This was about 30% of the U.S.A.'s economy. Some banks were sold cheaply, others were closed, and others became regulated banks. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac had $5 trillion in mortgage debts and were taken over by the government in 2008.

Exposition is not good.
It tells readers information, but does not make them feel. It is like telling instead of showing.
In story, exposition is when someone says a lot of information. In film, it is when one character tells another a lot of information.
Exposition should not be long. It should not be boring. Readers do not want too much information too fast.
It should show character, not just tell about them.
For example, do not say "They met, they married, he died." Show how they met. Show how they fell in love. Show what he was like. Show how she felt about him. Then show his death.
Show his character. Show hers. Show their love. Show their life together.
Show the feeling, not just the facts.
Do not rush. Do not skip details. Do not assume readers know everything.
Instead, show the details. Make readers care. Make them feel.

I watched two news reports from Columbus, Ohio. The first was on NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The main story was about a man named Shad Hostettler who stabbed his wife in Ashley, Ohio. It did not say her name. They showed his picture and said he looked evil. They only spent two minutes on the story. I think that was enough.
The second story was about a shooting of Travis Buyers, 18, in the Sharon Woods area. He was critically injured. There were no arrests or suspects. The SWAT team was investigating. I thought this story was short. I noticed that this was a black man and he was from a black neighborhood. I have seen this many times: black people are often not given much attention when they are victims of crime. If a white person is in trouble, the media pays more attention.
The next story was about a bullet hole in a Med-Flight helicopter. They said the bullet was from a .22 caliber rifle. Crime-Stoppers offered a reward for information about the shooter.
Another story was about a robbery at a UDF on Clime Road. A dark-skinned black man robbed the store. He wore a hoodie and was about six feet tall and 150 pounds. They spent a lot of time talking about how black he was.
The next story was about rain and thunderstorms for Saturday. They said the weekend temperatures would be in the mid to low eighties. They used this story as a teaser to keep people watching.
One last story was about Rene Rodriguez, who was a convicted drug kingpin. He was sentenced to 300 months for distributing large amounts of marijuana from Texas to Ohio. They said he was Hispanic, but I don’t think that was important to the story.

Brothers have a special bond; it is strong and cannot be broken. This bond has many feelings: love, pride, jealousy, and anger. Brothers understand each other more than anyone else. They see their own reflection when they look at their brother. This bond shows true feelings, good or bad, in difficult times. These feelings bring big problems. To understand these feelings, one must deal with their effects. A brother sees himself as he is, not as others see him. His actions and their effects show his true character. In "The Scarlet Ibis", two brothers show this bond and its feelings. They go on a journey in a beautiful, colorful place. They feel disappointed and proud at the end. One brother lives, but the other does not. The story shows these things through the main character, Doodle. His feelings and thoughts show his actions.
The main character feels sad when his brother, Doodle, is born weak and sick. He wanted a brother to play with and learn from. He wanted Doodle to do things like hold his breath, run, and climb trees. He also wanted to race and sit together high up. But this was not possible because Doodle was very sick. The main character felt angry and even thought about killing Doodle. But Doodle's smile made him feel better. This shows he cared for his brother. The story shows the main character's feelings and actions.

The human brain is a complex system. It processes information. Technology has changed how we think about the brain. First, the brain was like a wax tablet, then a sheet of papyrus, then a book, and now a computer. These old ideas are not always right. They can make us think wrong.
Information starts with senses. Senses change things like touch, heat, sound, or light into brain signals. The brain changes these signals many times. It uses simple information about the picture. It also uses past thoughts to help. It decides if something is important. Your name is important. You notice it in a noisy room. The brain has many steps. It uses your attention to decide what to do.
The brain needs to remember things. There are different types of memory. First, it encodes information. It uses different ways to remember different types of things. Then, it keeps information. Some studies say working memory uses a short loop of neurons. Long-term memory is in proteins.
There are many ways to think about how the brain stores knowledge. Some use what people remember. Others use computer science. Others use how the brain works. One way is the semantic network. It has nodes for ideas. Nodes are connected if ideas are related.

Aldous Huxley writes about the danger of technology and capitalism in his novel, Brave New World. People in this story value the community more than themselves. They are taught to be happy and use things from when they are very young. The people are like pawns in a game. They do not have free will. The World Controller controls them. Huxley uses words from Marxist theory to show problems in the economy. He talks about false consciousness. People do not know the truth about other classes. They only care about their own needs. The people are happy with their place in the world. They do not question it. Love and emotions are not real in this world. People only care about their bodies and things. They do not care about others. This shows the bad side of capitalism.

I have been at University Park for two and half years, or four and a half semesters. For many students, getting around campus is hard. I was in East Halls dorm. It was far from classes. Walking to Willard building took 25 minutes. Today, that space has sports fields and new buildings. The campus keeps growing, so it's harder to move around. What's the best way to move? Bikes are good, but the campus needs to be bike-friendly.

I talked to a friend who bikes again. He said, "Bikes are great." They are the best way to travel. Bicycling is better than walking. I live off campus, near the center. This year, I bought a bike. I go to Thomas building every day. It takes 5 minutes by bike. Pollock Road is the fastest route. It's not always easy to bike or walk. If I didn't have a bike, walking would take 30-40 minutes each day. That's 2.5 hours a week. Without a bike, I would spend more time walking to and from classes and appointments.
